<font color="#FF0000">LEADERS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 31  7:51:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Our political leaders have been taking a real hit, here and in other discussion threads.  I agree that they were responsible for what happened, and that they made MAJOR mistakes, but I do want to say a word in their behalf (not exactly defense - then I'd be defending Tricky Dick!).  I do this because, if we are to avoid similar mistakes, we have to understand the people who made them.  I think the people who made these mistakes (Truman, Eisenhower, Kennedy, McNamara....) grew up in a certain climate with a certain set of experiences that pre-disposed them towards involvement in Vietnam.  It was not a lack of &quot;expertise&quot; (after all, that was McNamara's argument in &quot;In Retrospect&quot;).  There were people who knew better, and said so, to most of the folks in the above list.  These people were ignored, and it's useful to ask why.  It's not because these leaders were bad men (thus I would never condone the kind of monument discussed here earlier - piss tubes over the graves of Johnson &amp; McNamara), but because they truly thought Communism was our greatest threat, and that if we didn't stand up to it &quot;wherever it reared it's ugly head&quot; we'd be in dire straits.  Does &quot;Munich&quot; and Kruschev at the UN with his shoe conjur up any images for the rest of you?   In any case, we don't have to forgive 'em, we don't have to like 'em, but we sure as hell have to understand 'em.  &quot;The Irony of Vietnam:  the system worked&quot; is an excellent read to help out on this - it's by the Pentagon Papers guy (the guy who wrote them, not stole them), Leslie Gelb.<br>
To Nurse Ratchet - Here's one vet who welcomes your view, though I don't necessarily agree with all of it.  You must try and understand why some of us would react so strongly to what you said; we were the ones shedding blood for the cause, which many of us still believe in.
<p><code>-- miketol@mtco.com  (Mike Toliver) </code><p>


